        "answer_count": 4,
        "title": "Java Application/Thread Server",
        "body": "<p>I am looking for something very close to an application server with these features: <\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>it should handle a series of threads/daemons, allowing the user to start-stop-reload each one without affecting the others<\/li>\n<li>it should keep libraries separated between different threads/daemons<\/li>\n<li>it should allow to share some libraries<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Currently we have some legacy code reinventing the wheel... and not a perflectly round-shaped one at that!\nI thought to use Tomcat, but I don't need a web server, except maybe for the simple backoffice user interface (/manager/html).<\/p>\n\n<p>Any suggestion? Is there a non-web application server, or is there a better alternative to Tomcat (more lightweight, for example, or easier to configure)? Thanks in advance.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 2532538,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "containers"
        ],
        "score": 3,
        "accepted_answer_id": 2532550,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 199
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/c53d539b59c19087182f0b1c53bb52de?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 7450,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 12960,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/12960/brian-agnew",
                "reputation": 273383,
                "display_name": "Brian Agnew"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269773257,
            "creation_date": 1269773257,
            "body": "<p>Have you looked at <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OSGi\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">OSGi<\/a> ? You can load/unload <a href=\"http://www.javaworld.com/javaworld/jw-03-2008/jw-03-osgi1.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">bundles<\/a> (basically .jar files with metadata) independently of each other, and optionally define dependencies between these (with a software lifecycle defined such that bundles are aware of other bundles being loaded/unloaded).<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532594,
            "question_id": 2532538
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/enNdg.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 21994,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 53897,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/53897/thorbj%c3%b8rn-ravn-andersen",
                "reputation": 75391,
                "display_name": "Thorbj&#248;rn Ravn Andersen",
                "accept_rate": 56
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1269773524,
            "creation_date": 1269773524,
            "body": "<p>I have found the Jetty \"contexts\" concept very useful in handling applications (packaged as WAR's and with servlet context listeners), where the xml-file placed in contexts/ describe fully what you want to have started.  When you remove the xml-file again, the thing described is stopped.  <\/p>\n\n<p>If you do not start a server connector you will just have a start-stop thing which sounds like what you are looking for.<\/p>\n\n<p>Jetty can be made very small so the overhead is not bad.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532610,
            "question_id": 2532538
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d5f91983a9d9cfb69981b6108a63b412?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 11089,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 21234,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/21234/skaffman",
                "reputation": 404605,
                "display_name": "skaffman",
                "accept_rate": 91
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 2.5",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1269772251,
            "creation_date": 1269772251,
            "body": "<p>You could consider <a href=\"http://www.springsource.com/products/dmserver\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Spring dmServer<\/a>. It's a rather non-traditional appserver, with a very lightweight OSGi core (the web container is optional, for example), but it gives you classloader isolation and basic container services. It's not a JavaEE container, but comes with plug-in modules that are.<\/p>\n\n<p>You're stlll going to have to do a lot of work yourself, but the basics of dmServer are very sound.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 2532550,
            "question_id": 2532538
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2e0cf554b2f6c7b75ded2918fcb3d74f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
